Using frequency separation in @photoshop to retouch this portrait of @maria_jaramillo 

How I use Frequency Separation to Retouch Skin in Photoshop

1. Open your image in photoshop
2. Make two copies of the background layer and name layer one “Colors/Low Frequency and name layer one copy “Texture/High Frequency” 
3. Disable the Texture Layer and select the Colors Layer then at the top: click Filter -> Blur -> Gaussian Blur
4. Drag the radius to where the skin texture is blurred but you can still see the features of the face
5. Enable the the Texture Layer and select it. Then at the top: click Image -> Apply Image and then change these settings.  Change the Layer to Colors. Change Blending to Subtract. Set Scale to 2. Set Offset to 128. Hit OK. 
6. Go to your blending options above the layers and select Linear Light. 
7. Combine both the texture and colors layers into a folder 
8. Disable the Texture layer 
9. Select the Healing brush and you can hold ALT to select a similar spot and balance our the shadows and paint over any blemishes or wrinkles that you want to lighten up 
10. Enable the Texture layer and use the Healing brush to continue editing your image, make sure you are ALT selecting near skin samples to keep your image consistent. I personally like to keep the skin looking at honest as possible but this is your preference!

Trigger ⚠️ Warning - As someone who has first-hand experience at how terrifying it can be to have an interaction with an ill-intended photographer, it is a conversation that I unfortunately have far too often with models. And as common sense as it may seem to me now, many models who are just starting out don’t know. This has happened to male models as well, it can obviously be an unsafe industry - so I like to share experiences and hopefully make a difference and save someone from experiencing something that can be traumatic. I recently had a model who asked if she can bring her boyfriend and I said of course, she later told me she was terrified to ask me because she had never been told yes. In my experience, that is the starting point for red flags to come. 

⚠️I used to model, before I realized I wanted to be behind the camera. I’ve had a male photographer show me videos of their genitals while we’re making selections, I’ve had a photographer who was much older try to force me to drink underage and threw his beer at me when I refused, I’ve had a photographer take my photos and then when I refused to flirt with him, he created fake phone numbers to pretend to hire me for photos and try to get me to meet and do who knows what. Those are 3 out of countless stories. These are not the worst of my stories. 

Of course, this isn’t a gendered thing - I’ve also had a very terrible experience with a female photographer in Orlando. 

Please be cautious, please protect yourself. Please respect each other. Please be human. 🫶

A few things I wish I could go back and tell myself when I first started Photography. 
1. Direct your subjects - I was so afraid when I first started to tell people how to move. I was reading too much into their facial expressions, I assumed I was annoying them, or I just felt shy. But in reality - the second I decided I know what I’m doing - my photos instantly got 10000 times better! And everyone really appreciates direction. No one is ever 100% comfortable in front of the camera. 
2. Trust your vision - when I have a concept or visualize the result beforehand - I have to trust my gut to get there. I used to let people with dominating personalities take over and then I’d feel somewhat defeated and deflated during my editing process. Yes, it’s great to ALSO get their ideas and include them but make sure you keep creative direction - unless you specifically are hired to follow someone else’s.
3. Always show back of camera - this was something I started very early because when i dabbled in modeling, it helped me so much. I felt way better after seeing what was transferring behind the camera and I could adjust whatever I didn’t like. This is also a great way to communicate for someone less verbal, they can instantly see what you may not be able to put into words. 
4. Shoot on 2 SD cards and back up everything! If your camera allows it, shooting on 2 SD cards at once is a life saver. BACK UP EVERYTHING. I cannot express the feeling I had when my hard drive crashed after it was pulled out of my computer on accident. Or when we lost power during a lightning storm. Anything can happen. Save yourself and your photos. 
5. No. No I won’t do that, no I can’t take more on, no I can’t work with that person again, no I’m uncomfortable with that.
6. Charge your worth, charge properly. Keep in mind travel, child care, business expenses, the world around you. Don’t let yourself burn out trying to keep other people happy. You will be ghosted when you share your prices sometimes, and that’s ok. It isn’t your responsibility for everyone to have photos taken, there are plenty of people in the position to charge what they are looking for. It doesn’t have to always be you. (Cont.)

3 things I always recommend to anyone when they are looking for a photographer (outside of myself haha)

1. Do you like their work? Well, duh, of course this is most important, but even I have fallen victim of trusting how someone portrays themself on insta. They might be posting the three best shots they got at an event or session, ask to see entire galleries for samples. If your going to shoot at golden hour, in dim light, or using flash, make sure to see that they can handle that setting. If you prefer candid shots, make sure they specialize in capturing those and that you can SEE the proof. 

2. Contracts - ask for and review the contract, look at the important details. How many images will be returned, what is the timeline, will you receive sneak peeks? Are there extra fees you might have to pay? 

3. Do you get along? It can be uncomfortable to be in front of the camera if you aren’t a professional model, and most of us are not. It won’t help if you don’t vibe well with the person who seemingly holds the power! Make sure you’re hiring someone who will work well with you (and whoever might be in the photos with you) . You can establish this with a phone call, video call, or possibly meet for coffee if that is an option they provide. 

I’d love to hear if there are considerations you think are also key when someone is hiring a photographer! Drop them below 👇 😘

It is time to out the person who has been harassing me online. 

Let me preface this with the fact that I did not want to have to do this. I would have rather this person do the right thing and a) not create several fake profiles to leave terrible reviews on my Facebook page or b) delete them on their own accord. However, after weeks of deliberation, I gave them a chance to make the right decision and they did not. I discovered their identity the very next day after the first few reviews were created and have been sitting on this information and living in this feeling ever since. It’s time to put it out there. 

I will make a part two sharing the interactions I’ve had with this individual, over eight years ago. If you have had an experience with him, you are welcome to reach out to me - I do know several models and their stories already, and I support you.

PART 2 - there will be more. If you missed the first part, the reel posted right before this will explain why I am bringing out a story about someone from nearly 8 years ago. If you have been victimized by this individual, you are welcome to share your story with me privately or however you feel comfortable, I support you. 

This story takes place in Denver, my very first week living in a brand new state in my own apartment. I had just started a photography business and was hoping to make connections and friendships in the creative community. I was preyed upon.
Part Three
Part four
Part five
Part 6

Part Seven: The End 🫶

Sadly, this is a very common theme in the industry, as it has been in many industries. We need to do everything we can to advocate for ourselves and protect ourselves. When this happened to me, I was 25 and all alone in a brand new state. I’m also naturally an open book, blissfully optimistic and hoping to see only good in people… an easy target. Let’s not stay quiet. This wasn’t the first or even the worst thing that happened to me when I was modeling. This needs to end. 

And why did I tell this story? Because this Individual (Nate) has decided to come out the woodwork 8 years later to create several fake Facebook profiles to leave terrible reviews on my business page. I found out because he used the same profiles to leave his own business (Recklss Colorado) glowing reviews.
